This is consistent with vent-based carbon fixation logic and thermodynamic favorability of amino acid precursor formation at moderate hydrothermal temperatures (Amend & Shock, 1998; White et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Mineral-catalyzed reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS2), greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic, reducing hydrothermal pore waters"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate forms an imine/iminium with ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction to alanine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on Fe-S minerals is a canonical prebiotic route to amino acids, and pyrite photoredox/reductive amination chemistry supports the plausibility of keto-acid to amino-acid conversion even though specific alanine-from-pyruvate under these exact vent conditions remains a generalized network step (Nature Communications, 2024; Amend & Shock, 1998)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface photochemical generation of HCN feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated evaporitic pools under anoxic atmosphere; included as a connecting surface HCN source"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven surface photochemistry generates cyanide-bearing species from simple carbonyl and reduced nitrogen feedstocks.", "reasoning": "HCN is required by Strecker and cyanosulfidic chemistry and is a standard prebiotic surface intermediate. The deep review notes HCN oligomerization and cyanosulfidic networks as experimentally established for simpler products, though