upported route to the serine co-substrate needed for speculative tryptophan assembly (Li et al., 2024; Kirschning, 2022; Miller, 1953; Johnson et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of pyrrole from acetylene and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "378K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "NiS/CoS-like sulfide catalysis represented here within FeS-rich vent mineral assemblages", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anaerobic aqueous volcanic-hydrothermal conditions; 105C"}, "mechanism": "Acetylene and ammonia undergo sulfide-catalyzed heterocycle formation to yield pyrrole.", "reasoning": "Pyrrole formation from acetylene and ammonia under aqueous anaerobic hydrothermal conditions at 105C is directly supported experimentally, although the original catalysts were NiS and CoS. Because the framework requires specified hydrothermal minerals from the Fe-S set, FeS/FeS2 are listed as the vent mineral agents while the reasoning notes the literature precedent and the broader iron-sulfur-world compatibility (Seel et al., 2021; Russell & Hall, 1997)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Fe-rich saponite nanoreactor formation of indole", "inputs": ["mol_002", "mol_003", "mol_001", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-473K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe2+/Fe3+-rich saponite nanopores with associated Fe-sulfide vent minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Lost City-type alkaline serpentinization environment, strongly reducing, moderate hydrothermal temperatures <200C"}, "mechanism": "Within Fe-rich clay nanopores, reduced gases and inorganic carbon are proposed to build the indole scaffold; pyrrole is included here as a plausible connected heterocyclic precursor feeding the unresolved annulation bottleneck.", "reasoning": "M\u00e9nez et al. detected indole together with tryptophan, skatole, and hydroxyanthranilic acid in serpentinized oceanic lithosphere and proposed indole formation from H2, NH3, and inorganic carbon in Fe-rich saponite nanoreactors. The exact Earth-prebiotic mechanism is unresolved, and no direct pyrrole-to-indole conversion has been demonstrated; therefore this step is literature-grounded but mechanistically speculative at the detailed level (M\u00e9nez et al., 2018; Kaiser et al., 2024; Seel et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Confinement-assisted direct condensation of indole with serine to tryptophan", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none established; confinement in mineral or protocell interfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "geothermal cycling and compartmentalization to retain hydrophobic indole"}, "mechanism": "Serine provides the amino-acid backbone and indole acts as nucleophilic aromatic partner, mimicking the net transformation of biological tryptophan synthase but without enzymatic channeling.", "reasoning": "This route is explicitly speculative. The literature review identifies indole + serine as the modern biosynthetic logic, but emphasizes that no prebiotic condensation has been demonstrated and that indole retention is a major problem outside enzyme tunnels. It is included as a necessary biochemical connection consistent with the review's proposed experimental direction of testing indole in warm aqueous pools with serine and minerals (Palazzolo & Bhatt, 2020; Kirschning, 2022; M\u00e9nez et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Strecker-like conversion of indole-3-acetaldehyde to tryptophan aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_007", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 