ly highlighted in the report as plausible for serine (Kirschning, 2022; Li et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to serine from glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous Strecker conditions with later hydrolysis during thermal cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde enters Strecker chemistry via imine formation and cyanide addition, followed by nitrile hydrolysis to serine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research explicitly notes serine can form prebiotically by Strecker synthesis from glycolaldehyde or glyceraldehyde with HCN and NH3; this is one of the best-supported surface routes in the network (Kirschning, 2022; Li et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4), greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent gradient; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise mineral-catalyzed reductive carbon fixation yields a C3 \u03b1-keto acid analog of proto-metabolic pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included because hydrothermal \u03b1-keto-acid formation is central to the supplied framework and consistent with vent-based proto-metabolic chemistry, though not specific to tryptophan in the literature packet (Amend & Shock, 1998; Russell & Hall, 1997; Martin & Russell, 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS2), greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic hydrothermal setting; mineral-assisted reductive amination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-keto acid is aminated by ammonia and reduced on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces to the corresponding amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids is part of the required framework and consistent with the report's emphasis on pyrite/Fe-S minerals promoting amino-acid synthesis and photochemical/semiconducting amino-acid formation (Amend & Shock, 1998; Nature Communications, 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyrrole formation from acetylene and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"378K (105C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide mineral surfaces in volcanic hydrothermal setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anaerobic aqueous conditions; literature reports NiS/CoS specifically, represented here within required hydrothermal sulfide-mineral schema\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetylene undergoes sulfide-mineral-assisted oligomerization/cyclization with ammonia incorporation to form a five-membered N-heteroaromatic ring.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Directly grounded in the report's citation that pyrrole forms from acetylene and ammonia under aqueous anaerobic hydrothermal conditions at 105C over sulfide catalysts, establishing a realistic indole-precursor branch (Seel et al., 2021). Because the schema restricts hydrothermal agents to listed Fe-sulfide minerals, chemically analogous vent sulfide surfaces are specified while preserving the reported environment and temperature.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface acetylene aromatization to benzene\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400C local thermal event or UV-driven surface photochemistry\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile), montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"subaerial volcanic or high-energy surface setting; included as aromatic ring source, not as demonstrated tryptophan chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetylene oligomerization/trimerization under energetic conditions yields benzene as an aromatic C6 fragment.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report notes benzene formation from simple precursors is documented through acetylene trimerization under UV/electrical discharge or high temperatures around 400C, and Kaiser-related work supports aromatic ring formation from acetylene in astrophysical contexts. This step is included only as a contextual aromatic precursor and is not claimed to solve indole synthesis (Kleimeier et al., 2022; Kaiser et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Indole availability by exogenous delivery or unresolved terrestrial annulation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable; exogenous delivery or unverified annulation conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile), borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"This node represents literature-recognized indole availability rather than a demonstrated terrestrial mineral reaction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Operationally, indole enters the network either via extraterrestrial delivery after interstellar ice synthesis or by a still-undemonstrated terrestrial ring-annulation process from simpler aromatic/N-heteroaromatic precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature is explicit that terrestrial prebiotic indole synthesis has not been demonstrated, while indole formation from acetylene and ammonia in interstellar ices is experimentally established. This reaction is therefore an intentionally marked placeholder/convergence node for indole availability, not a claim of solved Earth chemistry (Kaiser et al., 2024; M\u00e9nez et al., 2018; Kirschning, 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Formation of indole-3-acetaldehyde from indole and C2 carbonyl feedstock\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"speculative prebiotic carbonyl elaboration; included only to connect the documented theoretical Strecker route\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Indole C3 electrophilic substitution/carbonyl elaboration yields the indole-3-ethyl aldehyde framework required for Strecker chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report states that Strecker synthesis from indole-3-acetaldehyde is theoretically sound but that indole-3-acetaldehyde has no known prebiotic source. This reaction is therefore explicitly speculative and included only because the literature identifies this intermediate as the key entry to the Strecker branch (Kirschning, 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of tryptophan aminonitrile from indole-3-acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous Strecker conditions in concentrated pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Indole-3-acetaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia; cyanide attack gives the corresponding \u03b1-aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the literature-recognized chemically sound route toward tryptophan once indole-3-acetaldehyde is available. The report specifically identifies this transformation as theoretically sound though lacking a prebiotic source for the aldehyde precursor (Kirschning, 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of tryptophan aminonitrile to tryptophan\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis during geothermal or wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential nitrile hydration and hydrolysis convert the aminonitrile to the \u03b1-amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is standard Strecker completion chemistry and is the least problematic part of the theoretical indole-3-acetaldehyde route to tryptophan (Kirschning, 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Fe-rich saponite nanopore Friedel-Crafts-type tryptophan formation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Fe-rich saponite clay\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-363K (<200C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+/Fe3+-substituted saponite nanopores\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline serpentinization environment, strongly reducing, H2-rich, confined clay nanoreactors\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Confinement in Fe-rich saponite nanopores promotes a Friedel-Crafts-type C3 alkylation of indole by an alanyl-equivalent side chain under reducing hydrothermal conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction encodes the central M\u00e9nez hypothesis: abiotic tryptophan identified in Lost City-type serpentinites is proposed to arise by Fe-saponite-catalyzed Friedel-Crafts alkylation after indole generation in a serpentinization setting. The exact molecular sequence is unresolved and unreplicated, so this node is evidence-based but mechanistically conditional rather than laboratory-demonstrated (M\u00e9nez et al., 2018; Proskurowski et al., 2008; Russell & Hall, 1997; Martin & Russell, 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Conditional indole-serine condensation to tryptophan in confined prebiotic microenvironments\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"requires confinement or membranes/mineral interfaces to retain hydrophobic indole; highly speculative\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A nonenzymatic analogue of the modern tryptophan synthase logic is posited in which indole reacts with a serine-derived electrophilic intermediate to furnish tryptophan.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included only as a speculative connector because the report explicitly states that direct prebiotic coupling of indole with serine has not been demonstrated and is kinetically problematic, especially because even biology uses substrate channeling to manage free indole. Its inclusion addresses the literature's identified experimental frontier rather than claiming support (Palazzolo & Bhatt, 2020; Kirschning, 2022; M\u00e9nez et al., 2018).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"M\u00e9nez hydrothermal route via alanine-side-chain Friedel-Crafts capture\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation produces pyruvate and alanine, while indole is available through the unresolved-but-supported hydrothermal/exogenous branch; Fe-rich saponite nanopores then provide the literature-based hydrothermal tryptophan hypothesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Exogenous indole plus hydrothermal alanine route\",\n      \"description\": \"A simplified traversal emphasizing that indole may arrive exogenously while alanine is formed hydrothermally, converging in Fe-saponite nanopores.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Indole-3-acetaldehyde Strecker route from glycolaldehyde branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal C1 chemistry feeds surface sugar chemistry; glycolaldehyde is also used as the carbonyl feedstock for the speculative formation of indole-3-acetaldehyde, then the literature-recognized Strecker route reaches tryptophan.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Full surface serine plus indole-3-acetaldehyde branch\",\n      \"description\": \"A longer route showing hydrothermal C1 production, surface formose chemistry, serine synthesis, and the parallel indole-3-acetaldehyde Strecker branch before final hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolaldehyde-derived serine with speculative direct indole condensation\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation supports surface sugar and serine synthesis; indole availability then converges with serine in a highly speculative nonenzymatic condensation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyceraldehyde-derived serine with speculative direct indole condensation\",\n      \"description\": \"Alternative serine branch using glyceraldehyde as Strecker precursor before convergence with indole.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyrrole-led indole branch into indole-3-acetaldehyde Strecker chemistry\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyrrole formation from acetylene and ammonia feeds the unresolved indole bottleneck, then enters the conditional aldehyde/Strecker route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Shortest conditional Strecker path from supplied indole\",\n      \"description\": \"A minimal route reflecting the report's statement that once indole-3-acetaldehyde exists, the Strecker path is chemically sound.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface integrated route with both sugar and pyrrole convergence\",\n      \"description\": \"Shows environmental interconnection explicitly: hydrothermal C1 chemistry feeds surface sugar chemistry while hydrothermal acetylene-ammonia chemistry feeds pyrrole; both converge at indole and then at tryptophan through the Strecker branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-convergence route through serine and hydrothermal saponite nanoreactors\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate/alanine chemistry and surface serine chemistry are both represented, but the final target is assigned to the Fe-saponite hydrothermal route because that is the only direct evidence-bearing tryptophan context in the literature.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Tryptophan", "overall_strategy": "This network is an explicitly literature-constrained hypothesis graph for prebiotic tryptophan centered on the experimentally supported bottleneck that indole formation is unresolved on Earth. The network therefore uses only routes documented in the supplied literature: (i) hydrothermal serpentinization and iron-sulfur carbon fixation to produce simple carbon and amino-acid precursors, (ii) surface Strecker and formose chemistry to produce serine and related intermediates, (iii) hydrothermal pyrrole formation from acetylene and ammonia, (iv) interstellar/exogenous delivery of indole to the early Earth, and (v) two conditional tryptophan-forming branches recognized in the literature: the M\u00e9nez Fe-rich saponite Friedel-Crafts hypothesis and the theoretically sound Strecker route from indole-3-acetaldehyde. The 10 listed pathways are alternative traversals through a single connected bipartite graph; several are explicitly marked speculative where the literature says no demonstrated prebiotic reaction exists.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCOOH", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H7NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxypropanoic acid", "common_name": "serine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO3/c4-2(3(6)7)1-5/h2,5H,1,4H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C2H2", "iupac_name": "ethyne", "common_name": "acetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H5N", "iupac_name": "1H-pyrrole", "common_name": "pyrrole", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H5N/c1-2-4-5-3-1/h1-5H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C6H6", "iupac_name": "benzene", "common_name": "benzene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H6/c1-2-4-6-5-3-1/h1-6H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C8H7N", "iupac_name": "1H-indole", "common_name": "indole", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C8H7N/c1-2-4-8-7(3-1)5-6-9-8/h1-6,9H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C10H9NO", "iupac_name": "2-(1H-indol-3-yl)ethanal", "common_name": "indole-3-acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C10H9