ther": "subseafloor reducing conditions; treated as a connecting reduction step"}, "mechanism": "Further reduction of a C1 carboxylate equivalent on iron-bearing mineral surfaces affords a more reduced aldehyde-level carbon intermediate.", "reasoning": "This is a conservative connector motivated by hydrothermal CO2 hydrogenation/Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on iron minerals; the exact formate-to-formaldehyde conversion is less directly demonstrated than formate formation and is included as a necessary but partially speculative link to literature-supported sugar chemistry (Amend & Shock, 1998; White et al., 2015; Santos-Carballal et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formose entry: formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite), montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool or geothermal field, wet-dry concentration, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Base/mineral-assisted carbonyl coupling within formose-like chemistry generates the C2 sugar aldehyde; borate helps stabilize carbohydrate products.", "reasoning": "Grounded in classic formose chemistry from formaldehyde and the literature emphasis that glyceraldehyde/serine precursors arise from formose-type networks, with borate stabilization of sugars in surface settings (Butlerow, 1861; Breslow, 1959; Li et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Aldol extension to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite), montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycles in evaporitic pools; borate stabilizes trioses"}, "mech