": 0.68, "environmental_progression": 0.79, "target_achievement": 0.45, "overall_confidence": 0.53, "feedback": "This pathway is similar to P5 but uses the glyceraldehyde-serine branch. Upstream chemistry is acceptable, but the terminal step remains the core failure: there is no demonstrated prebiotic analogue of the tryptophan synthase indole + serine condensation. The literature in fact underscores why this reaction is difficult even in biology. As such, the pathway is connected but not chemically convincing.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_016"], "suggestions": ["Retain this only as a low-confidence exploratory branch.", "Explicitly note that biological substrate channeling has no clear prebiotic analogue here.", "Prioritize branches tied to field evidence or exogenous indole rather than unsupported direct condensation."]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_009": 0.82, "rxn_010": 0.63, "rxn_011": 0.18, "rxn_012": 0.2, "rxn_013": 0.73, "rxn_014": 0.83}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.49, "pathway_coherence": 0.63, "environmental_progression": 0.66, "target_achievement": 0.64, "overall_confidence": 0.5, "feedback": "This pathway is dominated by two unresolved aromatic steps in succession: pyrrole/benzene to indole and indole to indole-3-acetaldehyde. While pyrrole formation from acetylene and ammonia has support, and benzene formation from acetylene is plausible, the fusion to indole is precisely the missing prebiotic transformation highlighted by the literature. Combining two speculative aromatic steps makes this branch especially weak.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "suggestions": ["Do not present this as a competitive route to target under current literature constraints.", "Split astrophysical indole formation from terrestrial aromatic chemistry to better reflect evidence.", "Flag the annulation step as the principal unresolved bottleneck."]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "reaction_scores": {"r