 is foundational to alkaline vent carbon fixation models and is consistent with vent chimney mineralogy and geochemical plausibility (Russell & Hall, 1997; Martin & Russell, 2007; White et al., 2015; Santos-Carballal et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal reduced-carbon diversification to formaldehyde and pyruvate-equivalent pool", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "strongly reducing, subseafloor/alkaline vent interface; network-bridging abstraction of vent carbon fixation products"}, "mechanism": "Successive CO2/formate reduction and C-C bond-forming vent chemistry generate a reduced carbon pool feeding aldehydes and alpha-keto acids.", "reasoning": "Direct one-step experimental conversion to both formaldehyde and pyruvate is not established; this node is a conservative network abstraction representing hydrothermal reduced-carbon output that underpins prebiotic alpha-keto acid chemistry. It is included strictly to connect literature-supported vent fixation chemistry to downstream amino acid and sugar precursor chemistry; pyruvate formation from hydrothermal CO2/H2 systems is discussed in vent-origin frameworks, while amino acid formation from CO2/NH4+/H2 becomes thermodynamically favorable at hydrothermal conditions (Amend & Shock, 1998; Russell & Hall, 1997; Martin & Russell, 2007)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic, reducing vent microenvironment"}, "mechanism": "Surface-mediated reductive amination of an alpha-keto acid to the corresponding amino acid.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on sulfide minerals is consistent with hydrothermal amino acid synthesis models; pyrite photochemical reductive amination and Fe-S catalysis support alpha-keto acid to amino acid conversion under plausible prebiotic conditions (Amend & Shock, 1998; Nature Communications, 2024; White et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface UV generation and concentration of HCN/formamide cyanide pool", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide mineral-assisted photochemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "strong UV, evaporitic concentration, anoxic surface pools"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical and dehydration chemistry generates a reactive nitrile/amide pool including HCN and formamide from simple C1 and nitrogen feedstocks.", "reasoning": "This is a necessary connecting step rather than a single directly demonstrated reaction under the exact stoichiometry shown. The literature supports central roles for HCN and formamide in prebiotic surface chemistry and UV-driven networks, while TiO2 catalyzes formamide-derived heterocycle chemistry and sulfide photoredox systems support cyanosulfidic chemistry. Included as a cautious feedstock-pool abstraction, not as a validated dedicated HCN synthesis experiment for tryptophan (Patel et al., 2015; Saladino et al., 2012; Saladino et al., 2003)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Borate-stabilized formose entry to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pools, wet-dry cycling, alkaline episodes"}, "mechanism": "Formose-type aldol network produces small sugars; borate stabilizes pentose/triose intermediates and suppresses decomposition.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde are established products/intermediates in formaldehyde-derived sugar networks, although selectivity is poor. This is represented as a pooled output rather than an unrealistically single clean step, addressing prior over-compression concerns (Butlerow, 1861; Breslow, 1959; cited in the research summary for formose chemistry and sugar precursor generation)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Strecker-type serine synthesis from glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted aqueous Strecker/hydrolysis sequence", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool concentration followed by hydrolytic workup"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde imination with ammonia, cyanide addition to aminonitrile, then hydrolysis to the amino acid.", "reasoning": "Serine is one of the more plausible prebiotic amino acids and is discussed in the literature as accessible from glycolaldehyde or glyceraldehyde through Strecker logic; the displayed reaction compresses aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis into one network node for tractability (Kirschning, 2022; Li et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Alternative Strecker-type serine synthesis from glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted aqueous Strecker/hydrolysis sequence", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycles, concentration in shallow pools"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde-to-aminonitrile Strecker sequence followed by hydrolysis to serine.", "reasoning": "The literature explicitly notes glycolaldehyde or glyceraldehyde as plausible serine precursors in prebiotic chemistry. This provides a second convergent route to the serine hub (Kirschning, 2022; Li et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Hydrothermal pyrrole synthesis from acetylene and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "378K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "sulfide mineral hydrothermal analog; literature specifically used NiS/CoS", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anaerobic volcanic-hydrothermal setting; network uses Fe-sulfide analogs to satisfy schema while noting literature metal sulfides"}, "mechanism": "Acetylene-ammonia coupling on metal sulfide surfaces gives N-heterocycle formation.", "reasoning": "Pyrrole formation from acetylene and ammonia under aqueous anaerobic catalytic conditions is experimentally supported, though the published catalysts were NiS and CoS rather than Fe-only phases. This reaction is included because pyrrole is one of the few documented prebiotic heteroaromatic precursors relevant to indole chemistry (Seel et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Indole delivery/availability node from exogenous and hydrothermal sources", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_012", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["iron-rich saponite", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "278-363K hydrothermal; 5-10K in interstellar precursor stage", "pressure": "mixed: extraterrestrial low-pressure source plus hydrothermal emplacement", "catalyst": "iron-rich saponite as concentrator; interstellar energetic processing for source formation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "represents two evidence lines: exogenous indole formation and natural hydrothermal occurrence; terrestrial de novo indole synthesis remains unverified"}, "mechanism": "Network convergence node for indole availability through exogenous delivery and/or unresolved hydrothermal generation in serpentinization environments.", "reasoning": "This reaction is intentionally marked as a source-availability abstraction rather than a validated terrestrial annulation reaction. Indole was directly observed from acetylene/ammonia interstellar ice chemistry, and indole was also detected in Atlantis Massif serpentinites associated with putative abiotic organosynthesis. No prebiotic Earth laboratory route from pyrrole to indole is known, so this node avoids claiming a solved mechanism (Kaiser et al., 2024; M\u00e9nez et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Fe-rich saponite nanoconfined hydrothermal tryptophan-forming branch", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_011", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_015", "mol_019"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["iron-rich saponite", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-473K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "Fe2+/Fe3+-substituted saponite nanopores", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline pH 9-11, serpentinization-derived H2/NH3, reducing nanoconfined microreactors, Lost City-type system"}, "mechanism": "Fe-rich clay nanoconfinement promotes aromatic side-chain installation/Friedel-Crafts-like chemistry and associated aromatic amino-acid precursor formation.", "reasoning": "This is the core literature-grounded but unreplicated hydrothermal hypothesis. M\u00e9nez et al. reported abiotic tryptophan together with indole, skatole, and hydroxyanthranilate in iron-rich saponite nanopores from serpentinites and proposed Fe-saponite-catalyzed Friedel-Crafts alkylation under alkaline reducing hydrothermal conditions. Because the exact sequence is unresolved, this node outputs tryptophan and two observed/rel