onfidence\": 0.74,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is the best systems-level pathway because it explicitly compares the two major endgames in the literature landscape: the M\u00e9nez hydrothermal branch and the theoretical Strecker branch from indole-3-acetaldehyde. It excellently captures convergence and environmental interconnection. However, as chemistry it compounds the two major bottlenecks rather than resolving them: terrestrial indole formation and prebiotic indole-3-acetaldehyde generation.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_009\",\n        \"rxn_010\",\n        \"rxn_011\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"This pathway would benefit from explicit uncertainty annotation on all bottleneck nodes\",\n        \"Separate evidence-backed branches from speculative connectors more sharply\",\n        \"Add literature citations and exact mineral/condition details per reaction to improve alignment and evaluability\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.71,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is topologically solid and commendably literature-aware about the central unsolved nature of prebiotic tryptophan synthesis. It includes enough molecules and reactions, identifies sensible hubs, and provides multiple convergent routes centered on indole, serine, alanine, and aminonitrile logic. Environmental interconnection is a major strength: hydrothermal reduced-carbon chemistry feeds surface cyanide/sugar chemistry, and surface products feed biochemical or hydrothermal endgames. However, the network falls well short of approval because its key target-forming steps rest on precisely the unresolved gaps highlighted in the supplied literature. The largest issues are: (1) rxn_009 effectively asserts terrestrial hydrothermal indole formation from pyrrole/acetylene/ammonia, despite the literature stating this has not been demonstrated; (2) rxn_010 conflates